    A <fr:em>mixed Hodge structure <fr:tex>H</fr:tex> consists of</fr:em>

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;a. &quot;">
        A <fr:tex>\mathbb {Z}</fr:tex>-module <fr:tex>H_ \mathbb {Z}</fr:tex> of finite type, called the "<fr:em>integral lattice</fr:em>";
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;b. &quot;">
        A finite increasing filtration <fr:tex>W_n</fr:tex> on <fr:tex>H_ \mathbb {Q} = \mathbb {Q} \otimes _ \mathbb {Z}  H_ \mathbb {Z}</fr:tex>, called the <fr:em>weight filtration</fr:em>;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;c. &quot;">
        A finite filtration <fr:tex>F^p</fr:tex> on <fr:tex>H_ \mathbb {C} = \mathbb {C} \otimes _ \mathbb {Z}  H_ \mathbb {Z}</fr:tex>, called the <fr:em>Hodge filtration</fr:em>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol>


    We demand that, on <fr:tex>H_ \mathbb {C}</fr:tex>, the filtration <fr:tex>W_ \mathbb {C}</fr:tex> induced by extension of scalars of <fr:tex>W</fr:tex>, the filtration <fr:tex>F</fr:tex>, and the complex conjugate <fr:tex>\bar {F}</fr:tex> form a system <fr:tex>(W_ \mathbb {C} ,F, \bar {F})</fr:tex> of three opposite filtrations (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.7"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.7.xml"
taxon="Definition"
number="1.2.7"></fr:ref> and <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.13"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.13.xml"
number="1.2.13"></fr:ref>).
  </fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:context><fr:related><fr:tree
